VL  - 88
IS  - 4
KW  - Asset pricing
KW  - real estate
KW  - rational bubbles
KW  - transversality condition
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA16447
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Giglio, Maggiori, and Stroebel (2016) show that there is no significant price difference between freeholds and ultra-long leaseholds in the UK housing market. They claim that this finding precludes the presence of large rational bubbles, as these can only attach to the price of freeholds. But the conclusion presumes that leaseholders cannot acquire bubbles through enfranchisement at favorable prices. We find that the presumption is violated. Enfranchisement rights are comprehensive and cheap to exercise. We also dispute the counter-argument that cheap enfranchisement proves that market participants, if they have rational expectations, must have explicitly concluded that freehold prices are bubbleless.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Reply to “Rational Bubbles in UK Housing Markets”
AU  - Giglio, Stefano
AU  - Maggiori, Matteo
AU  - Stroebel, Johannes
Y1  - 2020/07/01
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2020/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA18174
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 1767
EP  - 1770
VL  - 88
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA18174
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In Giglio, Maggiori, and Stroebel (2016), we propose and implement a new test for classic rational bubbles. Such bubbles derive their value from each agent's rational expectation of being able to resell the bubble claims to the next agent. Backward induction ensures that classic rational bubbles can only exist on infinite-maturity assets. Our empirical exercise shows that infinite-maturity claims and 999-year claims for otherwise identical housing assets trade at the same price, and thus rules out the presence of classic rational bubbles. Domeij and Ellingsen (DE) informally propose an alternative equilibrium of a bubble that they claim is consistent with our empirical findings. DE's bubble relies on information frictions such that market participants are unaware of the bubble. Our paper clearly excluded this type of bubble from the scope of our test, and DE's note thus has no implications for the validity of our test. Instead, DE's bubble simply represents one of many possible examples of bubbles on which our test was explicitly silent.
ER  - 

